some domains can really benifit from the diamond topology. I think
jumping right to the chaining solution would make an implementation
biased to the &#39;diamond&#39; topology. That might be good for some domains,
and bad for others. Chaining also adds three pieces of structure that
might not be related to anything, where breaking and adding adds two
pieces to something that already exists, and so is certainly related. 
I think the sensible way to analyze a solution is by the number of
mutations required to get to some topology. John was counting 2
mutations one way, and 5 mutations another, versus 1 mutation by adding
chaining. My conclusion is that is would be most sensible to allow a
dissabled link to be reenabled, then broken again to create a new gene
that is effectivly identical to the previous break, but with a new
innovation id.
could the innovation id concept be expanded somehow to relate these two
genes, but keep them seperate?
chad


